    rationale: "TACROLIMUS MECHANISM (calcineurin inhibition pathway): T-cell activation: antigen recognition → TCR signaling → calcium influx → calmodulin binds Ca²⁺ → Ca²⁺-calmodulin activates CALCINEURIN → calcineurin dephosphorylates NFAT → NFAT translocates to nucleus → binds IL-2 promoter → IL-2 transcription → T-cell clonal expansion. TACROLIMUS: binds immunophilin FKBP12 → tacrolimus-FKBP12 complex physically blocks calcineurin's active site → NFAT stays phosphorylated in cytoplasm → NO IL-2 → NO T-cell proliferation → immunosuppression. Compare with CYCLOSPORINE: same calcineurin target but binds CYCLOPHILIN (different immunophilin) → cyclophilin-cyclosporine complex also inhibits calcineurin. GRAPEFRUIT INTERACTION: Furanocoumarins (bergamottin, 6',7'-dihydroxybergamottin) in grapefruit are MECHANISM-BASED ('suicide') INHIBITORS of CYP3A4 in intestinal epithelium. They bind CYP3A4's active site and form a reactive intermediate that COVALENTLY and IRREVERSIBLY inactivates the enzyme. Since tacrolimus undergoes extensive CYP3A4-mediated first-pass metabolism, intestinal CYP3A4 destruction → dramatically INCREASED tacrolimus absorption → supratherapeutic levels. This effect persists for 24-72 hours (until new CYP3A4 is synthesized). Tacrolimus toxicity: nephrotoxicity (afferent arteriole vasoconstriction), neurotoxicity (tremor, seizures), diabetes (beta-cell toxicity), hyperkalemia, hypomagnesemia.",
    explanationA: "Tacrolimus does not block TNF-α. Grapefruit INHIBITS (not induces) CYP3A4 → causing toxically HIGH levels, not subtherapeutic ones.",
    explanationB: "Correct. FKBP12-calcineurin-NFAT-IL-2 pathway blockade. Grapefruit's irreversible CYP3A4 inhibition increases tacrolimus bioavailability to potentially toxic levels.",
    explanationC: "Tacrolimus is not an antimetabolite (mycophenolate, azathioprine are). Vitamin C does not inactivate tacrolimus.",
    explanationD: "Tacrolimus does not block IL-6R (tocilizumab does). Grapefruit has no significant diuretic effects.",
    examTip: "Calcineurin inhibitor monitoring: tacrolimus trough levels (target varies by organ and time post-transplant). Common CYP3A4 interactions: INHIBITORS (raise levels): grapefruit, azole antifungals (fluconazole, ketoconazole), macrolides (erythromycin, clarithromycin), calcium channel blockers (diltiazem). INDUCERS (lower levels): rifampin, phenytoin, carbamazepine, St. John's Wort. The difference between therapeutic and toxic tacrolimus levels is NARROW — any CYP3A4 change can be dangerous.",
    category: "Pharmacology_Systems",
    subtopic: "Transplant immunology",
    difficulty: "hard",
    bennerStage: "expert",
    clinicalReasoningObj: "Trace the calcineurin-NFAT-IL-2 pathway and explain grapefruit's mechanism-based CYP3A4 inhibition as a life-threatening drug-food interaction",
    questionType: "advanced",
    clinicalTopic: "immunology",
    pharmacologyFocus: "moa,receptor_activity,drug_interactions,adverse_effects,contraindications",
    bennerBreakdown: "Expert transplant pharmacology requires understanding that grapefruit's CYP3A4 inhibition is IRREVERSIBLE (mechanism-based) — lasting days until new enzyme is synthesized — making it qualitatively different from competitive inhibition and potentially fatal with narrow-therapeutic-index drugs like tacrolimus."
