    explanationA: "IL-5 inhibition describes mepolizumab and reslizumab (anti-eosinophilic biologics). Omalizumab targets IgE, which plays a CENTRAL role in allergic asthma.",
    explanationB: "Correct. Anti-IgE (Cε3 domain binding) prevents FcεRI engagement → no mast cell degranulation → prevents both early and late phase allergic responses. FcεRI downregulation provides long-term benefit.",
    explanationC: "Omalizumab does NOT destroy B-cells — it only captures free IgE. B-cells continue to produce IgE, which is neutralized in circulation. This is why ongoing treatment is needed.",
    explanationD: "Omalizumab is not a histamine blocker. It works upstream — preventing the RELEASE of histamine (and leukotrienes/prostaglandins) by blocking the IgE-FcεRI interaction that triggers degranulation.",
    examTip: "Severe asthma biologics by phenotype: HIGH IgE + allergic → omalizumab (anti-IgE). HIGH EOSINOPHILS → mepolizumab/reslizumab (anti-IL-5) or benralizumab (anti-IL-5Rα). TYPE 2 INFLAMMATION (eos + IgE) → dupilumab (anti-IL-4Rα, blocks both IL-4 and IL-13). Tezepelumab (anti-TSLP) — works regardless of biomarker phenotype (upstream epithelial alarmin).",
    category: "Pharmacology_Systems",
    subtopic: "Anti-IgE therapy",
    difficulty: "hard",
