    correctAnswer: "B",
    rationale: "DUPILUMAB — DUAL IL-4/IL-13 BLOCKADE THROUGH SHARED RECEPTOR SUBUNIT: TYPE 2 INFLAMMATION in asthma is driven by TWO key cytokines: IL-4 and IL-13. They have overlapping but distinct roles: IL-4: (1) Drives naïve CD4+ T-cell → Th2 differentiation (via STAT6), (2) Promotes B-cell IgE class switch recombination (critical for allergic sensitization), (3) Upregulates VCAM-1 on endothelium → eosinophil recruitment. IL-13: (1) Goblet cell METAPLASIA → mucus hypersecretion (dominant driver of mucus plugging in severe asthma), (2) Subepithelial FIBROSIS (airway remodeling), (3) Airway smooth muscle HYPERCONTRACTILITY, (4) Induces periostin, FeNO (fractional exhaled NO). RECEPTOR SHARING: Both cytokines signal through complexes containing IL-4Rα: Type I receptor: IL-4Rα + γc chain → expressed on lymphocytes → IL-4 signals Th2 differentiation + IgE switching. Type II receptor: IL-4Rα + IL-13Rα1 → expressed on non-hematopoietic cells (airway epithelium, smooth muscle, fibroblasts) → BOTH IL-4 AND IL-13 signal through this → mucus, fibrosis, AHR. Dupilumab binds IL-4Rα → blocks BOTH Type I and Type II receptors → abolishes ALL IL-4 signaling AND ALL IL-13 signaling (because neither cytokine can activate its receptor without the IL-4Rα subunit). CLINICAL: LIBERTY ASTHMA trials: dupilumab reduced exacerbations by 47-70%, improved FEV1 by 130-200 mL, reduced OCS dependence. Also FDA-approved for atopic dermatitis, chronic rhinosinusitis with nasal polyps, eosinophilic esophagitis, COPD (eosinophilic), prurigo nodularis.",
