    explanationD: "IL-13 DOES use IL-4Rα — specifically through the Type II receptor (IL-4Rα + IL-13Rα1). This shared subunit is precisely WHY dupilumab blocks both cytokines. IL-13 has a separate low-affinity receptor (IL-13Rα2, a decoy) but its signaling receptor requires IL-4Rα.",
    examTip: "Asthma biologic target comparison: Omalizumab → free IgE (Cε3 domain). Mepolizumab/reslizumab → IL-5 (anti-eosinophil production). Benralizumab → IL-5Rα (direct eosinophil depletion via ADCC). Dupilumab → IL-4Rα (dual IL-4/IL-13 blockade). Tezepelumab → TSLP (upstream epithelial alarmin — broadest mechanism, works regardless of Type 2 biomarkers). Dupilumab uniquely spans multiple Type 2 diseases (asthma + AD + CRSwNP + EoE).",
    category: "Pharmacology_Systems",
    subtopic: "Anti-IL-4/IL-13 biologic therapy",
    difficulty: "hard",
    bennerStage: "expert",
    clinicalReasoningObj: "Explain how blocking a single receptor subunit (IL-4Rα) simultaneously disables two cytokine pathways by targeting a shared component of two distinct receptor complexes",
    questionType: "advanced",
