    rationale: "NALOXONE MECHANISM: Pure opioid ANTAGONIST — no agonist activity at any opioid receptor. COMPETITIVE BINDING: Naloxone has HIGHER affinity for μ-opioid receptors than morphine, heroin, fentanyl → displaces bound agonists within seconds of reaching the receptor. (1) μ1 REVERSAL: Restores consciousness (supraspinal analgesia/euphoria centers). (2) μ2 REVERSAL: The life-saving mechanism — restores respiratory drive. μ2 receptors in the pre-Bötzinger complex (medullary respiratory rhythm generator) → opioids suppress respiratory rate AND tidal volume → naloxone reverses both. (3) κ/δ REVERSAL: Reverses additional sedation, dysphoria (κ), spinal analgesia (δ). PRECIPITATED WITHDRAWAL: In opioid-NAÏVE patients, naloxone causes no symptoms (nothing to unmask). In opioid-DEPENDENT patients, chronic μ-receptor stimulation has caused compensatory adaptations: (a) LOCUS COERULEUS: Chronic opioid → suppresses LC firing (via Gi coupling). Counter-adaptation: upregulated adenylyl cyclase, INCREASED LC excitability. When opioid is abruptly removed by naloxone → massive noradrenergic surge from LC → sympathetic activation (tachycardia, hypertension, diaphoresis, piloerection, mydriasis). (b) GI SYSTEM: Chronic opioid → decreased GI motility (constipation). Counter-adaptation: upregulated excitatory circuits. Naloxone reversal → rebound hyperactive GI → cramping, diarrhea, vomiting. RENARCOTIZATION RISK: Naloxone t½ = 30-90 minutes (IV). Heroin (6-MAM/morphine) t½ ~2-4 hours. Fentanyl t½ highly variable. If opioid outlasts naloxone → respiratory depression can RECUR → patient needs observation for at least 2-4 hours after last naloxone dose. Repeat dosing or naloxone infusion may be needed for long-acting opioids (methadone, extended-release formulations).",
